## Design notes worth calling out

### Why the array stays sorted without sorting

Requests arrive in chronological order, so `push(now)` always appends the largest value. The array is born sorted and stays sorted — the eviction loop only needs a cheap linear scan from the front.

### The `retryAfter` math

```
retryAfterMs = (timestamps[0] + windowMs) − now
```

`timestamps[0]` is the oldest request still inside the window. It ages out of the window at `timestamps[0] + windowMs`, which is exactly when the count drops from `maxRequests` to `maxRequests − 1` and the next request becomes legal. No arbitrary "try again in 1 second" — the client gets the precise minimum wait.

### `X-RateLimit-Reset` semantics

Reports when the **oldest slot** in the current window expires (the count ticks up), not when the entire window resets. This matches [draft-ietf-httpapi-ratelimit-headers](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-httpapi-ratelimit-headers/) and is more useful to adaptive clients than a far-future full-reset time.

### `cleanupInterval.unref()`

Marks the interval timer as non-blocking. The Node.js process will exit normally if the interval is the only remaining callback — preventing hang-on-exit bugs in tests and one-shot scripts. The explicit `close()` method is still provided for deterministic teardown in graceful-shutdown handlers.

